@startuml 5G Concepts Explained

title Understanding 5G Data Channels - Simple Analogy

skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam roundcorner 10

' Analogy: Highway System
rectangle "🏙️ <b>ANALOGY: Think of a Phone Call as a HIGHWAY</b>" {

    package "OLD PHONE CALLS (3G/4G)" #LightPink {
        rectangle "Single Highway" #FFE4E1 {
            agent "🚗 Voice Lane" as OldVoice
            agent "🚙 Video Lane\n(if supported)" as OldVideo
        }

        note bottom of OldVoice
            Only voice and video.
            Can't send other data.
        end note
    }

    package "NEW 5G CALLS (What This SDK Enables)" #LightGreen {
        rectangle "Multi-Lane Highway" #E8F5E9 {
            agent "🚗 Voice Lane" as NewVoice
            agent "🚙 Video Lane" as NewVideo
            agent "🚚 **DATA CHANNEL Lane**\n(NEW!)" as DataLane #90EE90
        }

        note bottom of DataLane
            NEW: Dedicated lane for
            app data (menus, games,
            files, AR data, etc.)
        end note
    }

    OldVoice -[hidden]down-> NewVoice
}

' The Real System
rectangle "📱 <b>HOW IT ACTUALLY WORKS IN YOUR PHONE</b>" {

    package "YOUR PHONE (Android Device)" #AliceBlue {

        card "APP LEVEL\n(What you code)" #E3F2FD {
            component [Your Mini App\n(JavaScript/HTML)] as App1
            note right of App1
                You write: Vue.js, React, etc.
                Just like a website!
            end note
        }

        card "SDK LEVEL\n(This project)" #B3E5FC {
            component [IMS-DC-SDK\n(Android library)] as SDK1
            note right of SDK1
                Handles the complex stuff:
                - Creating data channels
                - Managing lifecycle
                - Bridging JS ↔ Android
            end note
        }

        card "HARDWARE LEVEL\n(Built into phone)" #81D4FA {
            component [5G Modem Chip\n(Qualcomm/MediaTek/etc.)] as Modem1
            note right of Modem1
                Physical chip that:
                - Connects to 5G towers
                - Manages radio signals
                - Implements IMS protocol
            end note
        }
    }

    package "THE NETWORK (Infrastructure)" #FFF9C4 {

        cloud "5G CELL TOWER" as Tower #FFEB3B

        cloud "IMS CORE\n(Telecom Company's Servers)" as IMS #FDD835 {
            component [Call Session Control] as Session
            component [Media Gateway] as Media
            component [Data Router] as DataRouter
        }

        note right of IMS
            **IMS = IP Multimedia Subsystem**

            Think of it as Zoom/Skype,
            but built into the 5G network
            by China Telecom/Mobile/Unicom.

            It handles calls over INTERNET
            instead of old cellular networks.
        end note
    }

    package "FRIEND'S PHONE" #E1BEE7 {
        component [Their 5G Modem] as Modem2
        component [Their SDK] as SDK2
        component [Their Mini App] as App2
    }
}

' Flow connections
App1 -down-> SDK1 : <b>1.</b> JavaScript API call
SDK1 -down-> Modem1 : <b>2.</b> AIDL command\n(Android interface)
Modem1 -down-> Tower : <b>3.</b> 5G radio signal
Tower -down-> IMS : <b>4.</b> Internet packets
IMS -down-> Session : <b>5.</b> Route call
Session -down-> DataRouter : <b>6.</b> Route data
DataRouter -down-> Modem2 : <b>7.</b> Send to other phone
Modem2 -down-> SDK2 : <b>8.</b> Deliver data
SDK2 -down-> App2 : <b>9.</b> Notify mini app

' Key terms explanation
rectangle "📚 <b>KEY TERMS DECODED</b>" #E8EAF6 {

    card "Terminal" #C5CAE9 {
        note as TerminalNote
            **Terminal = Your Phone's Hardware**

            In telecom language, "terminal"
            means the end device (your phone).

            <b>Terminal includes:</b>
            • Android OS
            • 5G Modem chip
            • IMS client software

            <b>Why we need AIDL:</b>
            The modem chip is separate from
            Android, so we use AIDL (Android
            Interface) to talk to it.
        end note
    }

    card "IMS (IP Multimedia Subsystem)" #9FA8DA {
        note as IMSNote
            **IMS = Modern Phone Call System**

            Old way: Calls use cellular network
            New way: Calls use 5G internet (IP)

            <b>Benefits:</b>
            • Better quality
            • Can add data channels
            • Can integrate with apps
            • Cheaper for operators

            <b>Standards:</b>
            • 3GPP TS.71 (Data Channel spec)
            • 3GPP TS.66 (WebRTC integration)
        end note
    }

    card "Data Channel" #7986CB {
        note as DCNote
            **Data Channel = Data Pipe**

            During a call, you have:
            • Audio stream (voice)
            • Video stream (camera)
            • **Data stream (NEW!)**

            <b>Uses:</b>
            • Send menu selections
            • Share screen
            • Play games together
            • AR/VR data
            • File transfer
            • Real-time translation

            <b>Technology:</b>
            Uses WebRTC (same as
            Google Meet, Zoom)
        end note
    }

    card "Modem/Chipset" #5C6BC0 {
        note as ModemNote
            **Modem = 5G Radio Chip**

            Made by companies like:
            • Qualcomm (Snapdragon)
            • MediaTek (Dimensity)
            • Samsung (Exynos)
            • HiSilicon (Kirin)

            <b>What it does:</b>
            1. Converts digital data → radio waves
            2. Sends to cell tower
            3. Receives from cell tower
            4. Converts radio waves → digital data

            <b>Why SDK needs it:</b>
            To create data channels, SDK
            must command the modem chip.
        end note
    }
}

' Summary flow
note as FlowTitle
<b><size:16>🎯 COMPLETE FLOW SUMMARY</size></b>
end note

[Start] as S0 #C8E6C9
[1. Mini app calls\nJavaScript API] as S1 #C8E6C9
[2. SDK processes\nrequest] as S2 #C8E6C9
[3. Modem creates\ndata channel] as S3 #C8E6C9
[4. Cell tower forwards\nto IMS network] as S4 #C8E6C9
[5. Data channel\nestablished!] as S5 #C8E6C9
[6. Both phones can\nsend/receive data] as S6 #C8E6C9
[End] as S7 #C8E6C9

S0 --> S1 : User taps button
S1 --> S2 : DSBridge translates
S2 --> S3 : SDK commands modem\nvia AIDL
S3 --> S4 : Modem sends request\nto cell tower
S4 --> S5 : IMS negotiates with\nother phone
S5 --> S6 : Ready to use!
S6 --> S7

note bottom of S3
    <b>AIDL (Android Interface Definition Language)</b>
    is like a translator between Android apps
    and low-level hardware/services.

    The modem chip isn't part of Android,
    so we use AIDL to talk to it.
end note

legend bottom
    |= Layer |= What It Is |= Your Control |
    | **Mini App** | Your HTML/JS code | ✅ You write this |
    | **SDK** | This project (IMS-DC-SDK) | ✅ You use this API |
    | **Modem** | 5G chip in phone | ❌ Phone manufacturer provides |
    | **IMS Network** | Telecom infrastructure | ❌ China Telecom/Mobile/Unicom operates |
    | **AIDL Interface** | Bridge between SDK and modem | ⚠️ SDK handles this for you |

    <b>Bottom line:</b> You only need to understand the Mini App and SDK layers!
    The SDK handles all the complex 5G/networking/modem stuff for you.
end legend

@enduml
